ns have distinct views on law.In Faith and Law, legal scholars from sixteen different religious traditions contend that religious discourse has an important function in the making, practice, and adjudication of American law, not least because our laws rest upon a framework of religious values. The book includes faiths that have traditionally had an impact on American law, as well as new immigrant faiths that are likely to have a growing influence. Each contributor describes how his or her tradition views law and addresses one legal issue from that perspective. Topics include abortion, gay rights, euthanasia, immigrant rights, and blasphemy and free speech.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristianity and law. 0aReligion and lawzUnited States. 7aLAW / Essays.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aFaith.  aadjudication.  abecause.  acontend.  adifferent.  adiscourse.  aframework.  afrom.  afunction.  aimportant.  alaw.  alaws.  aleast.  alegal.  amaking.  apractice.  areligious.  arest.  ascholars.  asixteen.  athat.  atraditions.  aupon.  avalues.1 aAprill, Ellen P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Anthony V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBost, Thomas G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaudill, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakrabarti, Kisor K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCochran Jr., Robert F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCochran, Robert F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurham, W. Cole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmon, Anver M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l